\subsection{Intersection cuts}
\label{sec:intersection-cuts}

We will now see study polyhedra of the form
\begin{align*}
  C & = \{x \in \mathbb{R}^n : x= \bar{x} + \sum_{j \in J} r^j
  \mu_j \text{ and } \mu \geq 0_{\vert J \vert} \} \\
  & = \bar{x} + \text{cone} (\{r^j\}_{j \in J})
\end{align*}
where $J$ is a finite index set and $r^j \in \mathbb{R}^n$ for all $j
\in J$. The vectors $r^j$ will be called \emph{rays} to be consistent
with most convex analysis literature. Since $J$ is finite, $\text{cone}
(\{r^j\}_{j \in J})$ is a polyhedral cone and hence $C$ is a translate
of a polyhedral cone. We will later (Section ??\fxnote{Missing
  reference!!}) see that these objects can be used to describe the
split closure of a general polyhedron completely. With this in mind it
therefore makes sense to study translates of polyhedral cones in
depth.

First we will derive what is known as the \emph{intersection
  cut}. In order to better understand what is going on we will first
consider an example before generalizing the concepts.
\begin{ex}
  Let $\pi^T x \leq \pi_0 \vee \pi^T x \geq \pi_0 + 1$ with $(\pi^T,\pi_0)
  \in \Pi$ be an arbitrary split disjunction and consider the polytope
  of Figure \ref{fig:splitTransCone}(a). Note that it is a translate
  of a polyhedral cone.
  \begin{figure}[htbp]
    \tiny
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}[>=latex]

      \fill[black!30!white] (0,0) -- (-4/3,2) -- (-0.8,2.15) -- (0,2.2)
      -- (0.5,2.15) -- (8/5,26/15) -- (0,0);
      \draw[fill, black] (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
      \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (-1,1.5);
      \draw[->, thick] (0,0) -- (1.2,1.3);
      \draw (0,0) -- (-4/3,2);
      \draw (0,0) -- (8/5,26/15);
